1

00:00:02,259  -->  00:00:06,199
The way we've been building confidence intervals thus far is

2

00:00:06,200  -->  00:00:10,070
based on bootstrapping and our knowledge of sampling distributions.

3

00:00:10,070  -->  00:00:12,919
This is an extremely effective method for building

4

00:00:12,919  -->  00:00:17,230
confidence intervals for essentially any parameters we might be interested in.

5

00:00:17,230  -->  00:00:20,839
However, if you've taken a statistics course elsewhere,

6

00:00:20,839  -->  00:00:22,370
you might be confused as to why

7

00:00:22,370  -->  00:00:26,445
this notation is different than what you've done in those other courses.

8

00:00:26,445  -->  00:00:31,879
You might have seen equations like these for capturing a population mean or proportion.

9

00:00:31,879  -->  00:00:35,149
Similarly, you might have seen equations like these for

10

00:00:35,149  -->  00:00:39,159
capturing the difference in means or the difference in proportions.

11

00:00:39,159  -->  00:00:44,884
All of these formulas have underlying assumptions that may or may not be true.

12

00:00:44,884  -->  00:00:50,344
If you truly believe that your data are representative of your population of interest,

13

00:00:50,344  -->  00:00:53,045
the bootstrapping method should provide

14

00:00:53,045  -->  00:00:56,899
a better representation for where the parameter is likely to be.

15

00:00:56,899  -->  00:00:59,494
However, with large enough sample sizes,

16

00:00:59,494  -->  00:01:01,519
these formulas should provide

17

00:01:01,520  -->  00:01:05,555
very similar results to those that we've seen in bootstrapping methods.

18

00:01:05,555  -->  00:01:09,000
In the next concept, we'll take a look at a few examples.
